An LRU (Least Recently Used) cache evicts the least recently accessed entry when capacity is reached. Achieving O(1) for both get and put requires combining a HashMap (O(1) lookup) with a doubly linked list (O(1) insertion/deletion and ordering).

The HashMap stores key → Node references. The doubly linked list maintains access order: most recent at head, least recent at tail. On every get or put, the accessed node moves to head. When capacity is exceeded, the tail node is evicted.

```java
class LRUCache {
    private final int capacity;
    private final Map<Integer, Node> map = new HashMap<>();
    private final Node head = new Node(0, 0);
    private final Node tail = new Node(0, 0);
    static class Node {
        int key, val; Node prev, next;
        Node(int k, int v) { key=k; val=v; }
    }
    public LRUCache(int capacity) {
        this.capacity = capacity;
        head.next = tail; tail.prev = head;
    }
    public int get(int key) {
        if (!map.containsKey(key)) return -1;
        Node n = map.get(key);
        remove(n); addToHead(n); return n.val;
    }
    public void put(int key, int value) {
        if (map.containsKey(key)) remove(map.get(key));
        Node n = new Node(key, value);
        addToHead(n); map.put(key, n);
        if (map.size() > capacity) {
            map.remove(tail.prev.key); remove(tail.prev);
        }
    }
    private void remove(Node n) {
        n.prev.next = n.next; n.next.prev = n.prev;
    }
    private void addToHead(Node n) {
        n.next = head.next; n.prev = head;
        head.next.prev = n; head.next = n;
    }
}
```

Time: O(1) for both. Space: O(capacity). Java's LinkedHashMap provides a built-in alternative via `removeEldestEntry`.

This is LeetCode #4. The naive merge approach is O(m+n); the optimal solution uses binary search on the smaller array.

Key insight: Find a partition of both arrays such that the left halves combined have exactly (m+n)/2 elements, and every element in the left half is <= every element in the right half.

Algorithm: Binary search on the smaller array (size m). For each partition i, compute j = (m+n+1)/2 - i for the second array. Check maxLeft1 <= minRight2 and maxLeft2 <= minRight1. If the condition holds, the correct partition is found.

```java
public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] A, int[] B) {
    if (A.length > B.length) return findMedianSortedArrays(B, A);
    int m = A.length, n = B.length, lo = 0, hi = m;
    while (lo <= hi) {
        int i = (lo + hi) / 2, j = (m + n + 1) / 2 - i;
        int maxL1 = i == 0 ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : A[i-1];
        int minR1 = i == m ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : A[i];
        int maxL2 = j == 0 ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : B[j-1];
        int minR2 = j == n ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : B[j];
        if (maxL1 <= minR2 && maxL2 <= minR1) {
            if ((m+n) % 2 == 1) return Math.max(maxL1, maxL2);
            return (Math.max(maxL1,maxL2) + Math.min(minR1,minR2)) / 2.0;
        } else if (maxL1 > minR2) hi = i-1;
        else lo = i+1;
    }
    throw new IllegalArgumentException();
}
```

Time: O(log(min(m,n))). Always binary search the smaller array to minimize iterations.

iOS image caching must balance performance (fast display) with memory efficiency (avoid OOM kills).

Two-tier cache: L1 is in-memory for fast access. L2 is a disk cache for persistence across launches. On request: check memory, then disk, then fetch from network.

NSCache for L1: NSCache auto-evicts under memory pressure and is thread-safe. Set `countLimit` and `totalCostLimit` (total bytes). Cost = width x height x bytesPerPixel.

Custom LRU for disk: A doubly linked list + HashMap tracks file access order. Evict the oldest file when total disk usage exceeds the limit (e.g., 200MB).

```swift
class ImageCache {
    private let memoryCache = NSCache<NSString, UIImage>()
    private let diskCache = DiskLRUCache(maxBytes: 200 * 1024 * 1024)

    func image(for url: URL) -> UIImage? {
        let key = url.absoluteString as NSString
        if let cached = memoryCache.object(forKey: key) { return cached }
        if let data = diskCache.data(forKey: url.absoluteString),
           let img = UIImage(data: data) {
            memoryCache.setObject(img, forKey: key, cost: data.count)
            return img
        }
        return nil
    }

    func store(_ image: UIImage, data: Data, for url: URL) {
        let key = url.absoluteString as NSString
        memoryCache.setObject(image, forKey: key, cost: data.count)
        diskCache.store(data, forKey: url.absoluteString)
    }
}
```

Memory pressure: Subscribe to `UIApplication.didReceiveMemoryWarningNotification` and call `memoryCache.removeAllObjects()`. NSCache handles this automatically but explicit clearing ensures prompt response.

Background prefetching: Use `UICollectionView` prefetching APIs to load images before they scroll into view.

Building a thread-safe KV store requires choosing the right synchronization strategy for correctness and performance.

ConcurrentHashMap: Java's ConcurrentHashMap uses lock striping — in Java 8+, it synchronizes on individual bins. Reads are lock-free (volatile). Writes lock only the affected bin. This gives O(1) average get/put with minimal contention.

```java
public class ThreadSafeKVStore<K, V> {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<K, V> store = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public V get(K key) { return store.get(key); }

    public void put(K key, V value) { store.put(key, value); }

    // Atomic conditional update (CAS)
    public boolean compareAndSet(K key, V expected, V newValue) {
        return store.replace(key, expected, newValue);
    }

    // Atomic compute — useful for counters
    public V computeIfAbsent(K key, Function<K, V> loader) {
        return store.computeIfAbsent(key, loader);
    }
}
```

Read-write locks for range operations: When consistent multi-key views are needed (e.g., range scan or backup), use `ReadWriteLock` — multiple concurrent readers hold the read lock; a writer acquires the exclusive write lock.

CAS retry loops: Read the current value, compute the new value, call `replace(key, oldVal, newVal)` — retry on failure. This implements optimistic concurrency without explicit locking.

Deadlock prevention: Acquire locks in a consistent global order. Never hold a lock while calling external code. Prefer `tryLock` with timeout over blocking `lock()` on critical paths.
